The most common way to terminate an unwanted pregnancy would be to induce labour before the third trimester or to take abortificients. Having an unattended miscarriage is highly commonplace among mainly impoverished women in rural Kiribati. Health care-centres are very reluctant, and will reject any patient who is suspected of having an unattended miscarriage, that wilful neglect of getting the abortion was a contributing factor to the death of a seventynine-year-old woman. The only other remaining option to not having the unplanned pregnancy would be that women would go seeking
abortion in Fiji and New Zealand, which many of them cannot afford to. In Kiribati, being pregnant is still a stigma and when women seek abortion after becoming pregnant, they would often hide it from their families and seek help from friends. Some doctors in Kiribati are willing to help but many are not willing to risk opening themselves up to being accused of being ‘illegitimate’ and had been cautioned by the local community and penalized by Kiribati's penal code.
